    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-01-13T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-01-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="704"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d704">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72112/3295</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at London</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SRP1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Skinner</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-01-13">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 13, 1917</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received 10.30 a.m.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Retaliation order, March 11, 1915,<note n="3" xml:id="d704fn3">
                        <ref target="frus1915Supp#pg_144">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ibid.</hi>, p. 144</ref>.</note> under which in effect
                    blockade is maintained, amended because of doubts as to whether the term “enemy”
                    in Articles 3 and 4 of said order includes any countries other than Germany.
                    Present amendment provides as follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>In Articles 3 and 4 of order of 11th March, 1915, terms “enemy
                            destination” and “enemy origin” shall be deemed to apply and shall <pb
                                facs="0665" n="493" xml:id="pg_493"/> apply to goods destined for or
                            originating in any enemy country, and the term “enemy property” shall be
                            deemed to apply and shall apply to goods belonging to any person
                            domiciled in any enemy country. Effect shall be given to this order in
                            the application of order of 11th March, 1915, to goods which previous to
                            the date of this order have been discharged at a British or Allied port
                            being goods of destination or origin or property which was enemy, though
                            not German, and all such goods shall be detained and dealt with in all
                            respects as is provided in order of 11th March, 1915.</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SRP1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Skinner</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
